I can see why people love Gary Danko so much. It's very classy, has excellent, courteous and attentive but not uncomfortable service, a mind-blowing wine list and comfortable seating arrangements. It was a tad cold for Ligaya and I, but I thought it was sweet they brought her a shawl when she commented on the temperature. It's a set menu, but you can pick the number of items you want - any number from any of the courses - and that determines the price of your meal. Since I'm a little lass, I picked 4 courses, two being the cheese cart and the trio of creme brulees. The cheese cart was a good choice since they have many unique, award-winning and intriguing choices, but the creme brulees were downright disappointing for me. They weren't sweet or distinct enough to be a trio of my favorite dessert. Sad. Also sad was two in our party feeling sick early in the meal to the point of having to excuse themselves to the bathroom for quite a while and feeling too wrecked to enjoy all their courses - we're guessing from too much oil in the lobster risotto, which was very tasty. On the bright side, I got to try more than my ahi tuna appetizer (very good but not unique) and beef tenderloin because the BF wasn't feeling up to eating all of his lobster and hen breast. The lobster was probably the most flavorful and tender lobster I've had, but the hen wasn't all that - seems like it could have been more tender and was basically just a big breast with seasoning on the outside and no flavor on the inside. My tenderloin was very well seasoned and the gratin was good, but, again, it could have been more tender. Overall, I really enjoyed Gary Danko, but since we were celebrating my new job, I was a little disappointed at my socks not being blown totally off by this place I've heard such great things about. Perhaps what I expect from a fine dining restaurant is flawless execution, not just yummy ideas, top notch service and atmosphere for days. This is a great spot for a fine dinner out and I'd gladly give it another shot to see if we just experienced some bad luck and if there is a truly awesome GD meal out there for me.

Wow is all I can say. The cauliflower food was surprisingly good. I don't like cauliflower and GD got me to finish a bowl of this creamy concoction, that's a fete. The butternut squash tart with onions and gruyere & goat cheese mouse was savory with a hint of tartness. My favorite dish was the herb encrusted tuna with creme fraiche. The herb crust was the perfect blend of seasoning to compliment the tuna. The foie gras with apples just melted in my mouth. The tender guinea hen was set on top of yummy chestnut gnocchi. The chocolate souffleé was spongy. For an extra touch, order the flambeed cardamom apples, at it is prepared and served table side. Oh and save room for the cheese platter! As expected the wine list is impressive and with the tasting menu, you can opt to have wine parings if you like. Depending on what day and time you dine, the ambiance can be low key and romantic. The way seating is arranged leaves little room to walk around the restaurant. There were times I thought the waiter would trip and drop the food. The service is impeccable. Our waiter made sure the dishes were to our liking and our wine glasses were never empty. This is a must on your list of restaurants but be prepared to spend a pretty penny here.

After two years of living here and professing to be a foodie, I finally made it to Gary Danko. The decor is a little boring and bordering on cheesy. The service was impeccable. The food? Spectacular. Went for the five course...lobster salad, foie gras (screw you, PETA), bison (!), cheese, and creme brulee. Did the wine pairing as well...go big or go home, as they say. If I could do it again, I think I'd have gone four courses including cheese because I was pretty food coma'd out by the end. GET THE CHEESE PLATE. The creme brulee was the only letdown, as it was done three ways and there was just too much of it. All the other courses were sized perfectly. The lobster was perfectly done, the foie gras seared perfectly, the bison wasn't gamy at all, and the cheese...ah, THE CHEESE!!!! Best dinner I've had in San Francisco. How this place only got one Michelin star is beyond me.

One word describes our experience at Gary Danko: impeccable. This cozy San Francisco gem, located on North Point and Hyde, orchestrates their service to perfection. The servers have perma-smiles plastered to their faces as they provide the most fluid and smoothest service ever in the history of waiter-dom. The servers appeared effortlessly - changing out flatware, refilling our glasses, taking dishes away. They asked questions without appearing overly eager, staggered out the courses so that we didn't feel rushed, and were so friendly, we couldn't believe we were at a nice restaurant. :) They've really eschewed the traditional concept of "fine dining". Gone are the days of overly formal and curt service and the days of stuffy interior design. The restaurant has a warm and intimate dining area with a few well spaced tables and booths. The dining room, with its dark wood paneling and intimate lighting, created a space that exuded restrained elegance. Lucky for us, we got the best table in the house: a small and cozy corner booth that overlooked the dining area. From where we were, we could watch people celebrate their birthdays; couples on first dates; and old, rich men with really young ladies. ;) Gary Danko offers a unique dining experience: there are three, four, and five course options. You choose how many courses you want, and then pick a sampling of dishes based on that number. We both chose the three course offering. Before our tri-course experience began, the server brought us a "treat from the chef": a small offering of chilled zucchini soup, which was reminiscent of a gazapacho soup. Then, after our tasty treat, they brought us blinis with caviar as an "apology for not having our table ready on time." It was a tiny mouthful of heaven. I'd wait the extra fifteen minutes again for another blini from Gary Danko. So, after all the delicious culinary fourplay, our real food started arriving. I started with the risotto. It was creamy and rich - cooked to perfection, while maintaining its al dente texture. There were bits of lobster, shrimp, zucchini and artichokes mixed in with the risotto, so you know I can't complain too much about that. For the second course, I opted for the branzani. I've never had branzini before, but our server helpfully explained that it's a flaky white fish cooked with the skin on - like halibut. I like halibut. And I liked the branzini as well. The fish was tender and melted in my mouth, and the skin was nice and crispy. They served it with a fennel puree and an orange and saffron sauce. The fennel puree tasted eerily similar to mashed potatoes. I was expecting it to taste more like an onion. Maybe I need to freshen up on my vegetables and herbs? There were no unexpected flavor profiles on the third course. Everything was satisfyingly familiar to my palette: lamb loin on a bed of roasted red bell peppers and zucchini. The combination of lamb and roasted bell peppers harmoniously complimented each other. I ate more than I expected. Oh, my food baby was pleased. We ended our meal with a trio of creme brulees: chai, expresso, and berry brulees. Gary Danko does NOT mess around with their creme brulees. They were some of the creamiest and most perfectly bruleed brulees I've ever had. At this point, I officially entered a food coma. Unfortunately (or fortunately) for us, Gary Danko sent out another dessert for us. A chocolatey chocolate cake to congratulate us for entering the adult world of pre-marital bliss. Yay, congratulations to us. And congratulations to Gary Danko, for creating an enviable dining experience other restaurants wished they could offer.

Ahhhhh the coveted Gary Danko. Considered by many to be the best restaurant in San Francisco, frequented by the higher echelon of society, and probably one of the most sought after destinations of Yelpers, who are truly dying to know.....is it worth it? With all of the hype surrounding this restaurant, I went in with a bit of a skepticism. No way can a restaurant can live up to THAT much anticipation. Before I get into the meat of the review, I'd like to point out that I personally believe in the entire dining experience. Meaning, a restaurant should have more then just great food, it most impress me with its ambience, hospitality, and unique attention to detail that distinguishes it from its peers. Now to the review... The night started out with us waiting 45 min for our reservations. The entire time I was bitter and devising the best turn of phrase to flame GD to the Yelp community for its horrible service. I should point out that throughout the entire night all of the employees were SUPER friendly. I say this with extreme emphasis cause never in my LIFE have I ever been to a place with more smiling faces and open hearts. Nonetheless, I had to wait for our seat and it upset me. As soon as we sat down, our waitress immediately apologized for our wait and gave us a free round of drinks and a free appetizer. No better way to get to this Yelpers heart then through his stomach. My temperament was mollified and I was once again happy to be in GD, giddily wondering if I was in the exact same seat as Michael Jordan when he came here after the President's Cup. On to the food. I go the 5 course tasting menu. To keep this relatively short and sweet I'll put this in a ordered format. Lobster Bisque: great texture and flavor. Most bisques I try are too watery and the temperature is too hot or cold, making it taste like some sort of consommé but GD got it right on the money. Oysters with Caviar: NOT oceany despite the oysters and caviar. simply refreshing with the light cream sauce drizzled over the oyster. Horseradish Crusted Salmon: Cooked to perfection. It really melted in the mouth and the dilled cucumbers gave it a nice little kick. Lamb: I must say this was one of the low point of the meal. The lamb shoulder was marvelous and great by all accounts but the lamb loin cuts were a bit off the mark by being a bit chewy from being slightly overcooked. Cheese: ummm not a big connaisseur of cheese. not even going to try to be pretentious and claim i could detect the slight oaky aroma coming from the gouda or the herby texture of the bleu cheese. it tasted how fancy cheese should taste. to each his (or her) own. chocolate souffle: now heres a dish I can get behind. The only way I can accurately describe this dish is the fact that after the cheese I was BEYOND stuffed and somehow the souffle was finished. A real testament to its quality and tastiness Overall, you won't get a similar experience to Gary Danko. I'm not use to super friendly service and it was very refreshing to see this. They also give you so many free extras that makes asians such as myself very happy.

stepping into gary danko is like stepping into a time capsule circa 1980s: completely blacked out windows, crystalline tree branches reflected by mirrors and just-so lighting, creating a dramatic main dining room focal point. tendrilous and elegant super flower bouquets mixed with black and gold masculine finishes. a small bar with a wine list the size of the new testament. gleaming cheese trays and dessert tiers, and an uber-professional staff that works the room like a well-oiled machine, complete with regular rotations similar to military mobilization. one thing's for sure: you will never find yourself wanting-- the service is PHENOMENAL. freebies: - a fun duck liver dumpling w/ carmelized onions and panko amuse bouche - truly delicious gary danko breakfast bun for the ladies (tasted like a carrot cake with cream cheese filling and top) and a leather pocket notebook for the men - gary danko matchbox giveaways (old school, baby!) i ordered the black truffle 5-course tasting menu with wine pairings (menu and wine pairings available on the GD website). all exceptional and beautiful. wines were presented and explained impeccably by master sommeliers, and the timing was perfect. one quip is that the black truffle wasn't as "truffley" as it could have been, that is-- the dishes presented were big on flavor and i expected more truffle in order for it to become the star. favorites: - the SO's red pumpkin soup with chive biscuit - crispy farm egg with white polenta and black/white truffles - seared scallops with parsnip potato puree and black truffle sauce - wine: 2004 barolo, massolino-- paired with beef tenderloin - cheese tray was super informative (up to 4 different cheese selections) meh: - black truffle cremeux dessert. it tasted really waxy to me. tip: book at least 6 weeks in advance. it's easier to reschedule/alter an existing reservation than to try and perfectly time your call for a specific date and time.

Actually, I would probably give this two and a half stars, if I could. Two seems a little harsh, considering the service was some of the best I've ever received, but the food was so many kinds of underwhelming I don't even know where to begin. This is one of those restaurants that you rank up there with Manresa, French Laundry, Boulud, etc. So you go in knowing you're going to pay the equivalent of a month's rent. But you've saved, it's a special occasion, you are prepared. You are also prepared to be wowed and dazzled like you've never been wowed and dazzled before. Wife and I went for my birthday. I was shocked when I called just five days before the day and got a reservation. I don't know if it's the economy or if more and more people are having the same experience I had there. Anyway, when I called, they asked whether it was a special occasion, and I told the reservationist that it was my birthday. We walked in and immediately the service was a cut above. We were so impressed with everyone from the valet to the hostess to our waitstaff, who knew the menu so well it boggled the mind. The sommelier was also personable and highly knowledgable, as one would expect. My wife and I each chose the four-course meal with wine pairings and settled in to be blown away. My first course was the crab salad with Meyer lemon aioli. I couldn't believe it--the crab was SWIMMING in aioli. Crab is a delicate shellfish, not something that should be drenched in mayo. My wife started with the lobster and rock shrimp risotto, which was unbelieveably salty. Not so salty it was inedible, but salty enough to where salt was the predominant flavor. Not to pick nits here, but I'm sorry, at a restaurant of this caliber you want no mistakes, and right out of the gate, with our first two dishes, were two seriously amateur mistakes. Over-dressing and over-salting can happen to the best line cook, but it's pretty irritating when it's happening during your once-in-a-lifetime dining experience at a restaurant you think should know better. My second course was the roasted lobster, which was over-cooked and slightly rubbery. Again, nothing up to this point was inedible, but it was just profoundly disappointing. My first two dishes were flawed in some very basic ways. Our third courses--the Guinea hen breast for me and the duck breast for my wife--were very well-executed. Her duck breast was probably the highlight of the meal. The duck hash it came with was stellar, perfectly cooked, perfectly seasoned. Wife got the cheese plate as her fourth course, which was mind-blowing. Again, our server did not disappoint. She definitely knew her cheeses and helped us select four that she thought we'd enjoy based on what we were telling her we liked. My trio of macaroons was also phenomenal. I'm not much of a dessert person, but these were out of this world. I should also state that the pairings the sommelier picked for us were spot-on. He did a fantastic job as well. The staff here is amazing. However, the final blow was that they sent out a cheesecake with "Happy Birthday" written on the rim of the plate, with a little candle. We hadn't ordered it, so I'm assuming they knew it was my birthday when I called and made the ressie. It was charming and a nice gesture. The cheesecake itself, though, tasted a bit like a Costco cheesecake. You know how sometimes lemony desserts can veer into that dangerous territory of tasting a little like lemon-scented Pledge? This was that. To make matters worse, when my wife checked her receipt the next day, she discovered that they had charged us not for two four-course meals, but for one four-course and one five-course meal, and we deduced that they must have considered my cheesecake as a fifth course...even though we didn't order it! It ceases to become a nice gesture when they charge you for it behind your back. Anyway, I'm not normally this nitpicky, really I'm not. If I'm at someplace like Delfina, I can overlook a line cook who got a little heavy handed with the salt or a shellfish that stayed in the pot a little too long. But when you're talking this level of professionalism and this price range, I'm looking for flawless. Interestingly enough, I've had several people tell me they also had the same underwhelming experience there as well. Yes the food was still well above average and some of it was even innovative (though not incredibly so). And yes, the staff here provides impeccable service. But overall, I couldn't help being disappointed as I walked away from Gary Danko. I'm glad I went once, just for the experience, but I don't think I'll be making a second trip. It'd be nice to go back to see if they were just having an off night, but unfortunately their prices preclude that, so I fear this will be my one GD experience, and it was pretty lackluster.

    3/2/2008

    I can see why people love Gary Danko so much. It's very classy, has excellent, courteous and attentive but not uncomfortable service, a mind-blowing wine list and comfortable seating arrangements. It was a tad cold for Ligaya and I, but I thought it was sweet they brought her a shawl when she commented on the temperature.

    It's a set menu, but you can pick the number of items you want - any number from any of the courses - and that determines the price of your meal. Since I'm a little lass, I picked 4 courses, two being the cheese cart and the trio of creme brulees. The cheese cart was a good choice since they have many unique, award-winning and intriguing choices, but the creme brulees were downright disappointing for me. They weren't sweet or distinct enough to be a trio of my favorite dessert. Sad. Also sad was two in our party feeling sick early in the meal to the point of having to excuse themselves to the bathroom for quite a while and feeling too wrecked to enjoy all their courses - we're guessing from too much oil in the lobster risotto, which was very tasty.

    On the bright side, I got to try more than my ahi tuna appetizer (very good but not unique) and beef tenderloin because the BF wasn't feeling up to eating all of his lobster and hen breast. The lobster was probably the most flavorful and tender lobster I've had, but the hen wasn't all that - seems like it could have been more tender and was basically just a big breast with seasoning on the outside and no flavor on the inside. My tenderloin was very well seasoned and the gratin was good, but, again, it could have been more tender.

    Overall, I really enjoyed Gary Danko, but since we were celebrating my new job, I was a little disappointed at my socks not being blown totally off by this place I've heard such great things about. Perhaps what I expect from a fine dining restaurant is flawless execution, not just yummy ideas, top notch service and atmosphere for days. This is a great spot for a fine dinner out and I'd gladly give it another shot to see if we just experienced some bad luck and if there is a truly awesome GD meal out there for me.

    Wow is all I can say. The cauliflower food was surprisingly good. I don't like cauliflower and GD got me to finish a bowl of this creamy concoction, that's a fete. The butternut squash tart with onions and gruyere & goat cheese mouse was savory with a hint of tartness. My favorite dish was the herb encrusted tuna with creme fraiche. The herb crust was the perfect blend of seasoning to compliment the tuna. The foie gras with apples just melted in my mouth. The tender guinea hen was set on top of yummy chestnut gnocchi. The chocolate souffleé was spongy.  For an extra touch, order the flambeed cardamom apples, at it is prepared and served table side. Oh and save room for the cheese platter! As expected the wine list is impressive and with the tasting menu, you can opt to have wine parings if you like.

    Depending on what day and time you dine, the ambiance can be low key and romantic. The way seating is arranged leaves little room to walk around the restaurant. There were times I thought the waiter would trip and drop the food. The service is impeccable. Our waiter made sure the dishes were to our liking and our wine glasses were never empty. This is a must on your list of restaurants but be prepared to spend a pretty penny here.

    9/20/2008

    One word describes our experience at Gary Danko: impeccable.

    This cozy San Francisco gem, located on North Point and Hyde, orchestrates their service to perfection. The servers have perma-smiles plastered to their faces as they provide the most fluid and smoothest service ever in the history of waiter-dom. The servers appeared effortlessly - changing out flatware, refilling our glasses, taking dishes away. They asked questions without appearing overly eager, staggered out the courses so that we didn't feel rushed, and were so friendly, we couldn't believe we were at a nice restaurant. :)

    They've really eschewed the traditional concept of "fine dining". Gone are the days of overly formal and curt service and the days of stuffy interior design.

    The restaurant has a warm and intimate dining area with a few well spaced tables and booths. The dining room, with its dark wood paneling and intimate lighting, created a space that exuded restrained elegance. Lucky for us, we got the best table in the house: a small and cozy corner booth that overlooked the dining area. From where we were, we could watch people celebrate their birthdays; couples on first dates; and old, rich men with really young ladies. ;)

    Gary Danko offers a unique dining experience: there are three, four, and five course options. You choose how many courses you want, and then pick a sampling of dishes based on that number. We both chose the three course offering.

    Before our tri-course experience began, the server brought us a "treat from the chef": a small offering of chilled zucchini soup, which was reminiscent of a gazapacho soup. Then, after our tasty treat, they brought us blinis with caviar as an "apology for not having our table ready on time." It was a tiny mouthful of heaven. I'd wait the extra fifteen minutes again for another blini from Gary Danko.

    So, after all the delicious culinary fourplay, our real food started arriving.

    I started with the risotto. It was creamy and rich - cooked to perfection, while maintaining its al dente texture. There were bits of lobster, shrimp, zucchini and artichokes mixed in with the risotto, so you know I can't complain too much about that.

    For the second course, I opted for the branzani. I've never had branzini before, but our server helpfully explained that it's a flaky white fish cooked with the skin on - like halibut. I like halibut. And I liked the branzini as well. The fish was tender and melted in my mouth, and the skin was nice and crispy. They served it with a fennel puree and an orange and saffron sauce. The fennel puree tasted eerily similar to mashed potatoes. I was expecting it to taste more like an onion. Maybe I need to freshen up on my vegetables and herbs?  

    There were no unexpected flavor profiles on the third course. Everything was satisfyingly familiar to my palette: lamb loin on a bed of roasted red bell peppers and zucchini. The combination of lamb and roasted bell peppers harmoniously complimented each other. I ate more than I expected. Oh, my food baby was pleased.

    We ended our meal with a trio of creme brulees: chai, expresso, and berry brulees. Gary Danko does NOT mess around with their creme brulees. They were some of the creamiest and most perfectly bruleed brulees I've ever had. At this point, I officially entered a food coma.

    Unfortunately (or fortunately) for us, Gary Danko sent out another dessert for us. A chocolatey chocolate cake to congratulate us for entering the adult world of pre-marital bliss. Yay, congratulations to us. And congratulations to Gary Danko, for creating an enviable dining experience other restaurants wished they could offer.

    4.5 stars.  You go to Gary Danko if you want a great solid meal with excellent and unpretentious service.  The interior is upscale, but not modern and the cliente is a mixed bag - some families, some people on dates and some older rich people.  Overall, the food was excellent (my veal breast was exceptionally tender and moist and the foie gras was perfect), but there were some misses (I felt that my lobster bisque while full of flavor, was slightly oversalted and my pan seared tuna was just so-so).  Again, as everyone knows, the best part of GD is their excellent service and attention toward customer satisfaction that draws the crowds.

    2/27/2010

    Ahhhhh the coveted Gary Danko.  Considered by many to be the best restaurant in San Francisco, frequented by the higher echelon of society, and probably one of the most sought after destinations of Yelpers, who are truly dying to know.....is it worth it?

    With all of the hype surrounding this restaurant, I went in with a bit of a skepticism. No way can a restaurant can live up to THAT much anticipation.  Before I get into the meat of the review, I'd like to point out that I personally believe in the entire dining experience.  Meaning, a restaurant should have more then just great food, it most impress me with its ambience, hospitality, and unique attention to detail that distinguishes it from its peers.

    Now to the review...

    The night started out with us waiting 45 min for our reservations.  The entire time I was bitter and devising the best turn of phrase to flame GD to the Yelp community for its horrible service.  I should point out that throughout the entire night all of the employees were SUPER friendly.  I say this with extreme emphasis cause never in my LIFE have I ever been to a place with more smiling faces and open hearts.  Nonetheless, I had to wait for our seat and it upset me.  As soon as we sat down, our waitress immediately apologized for our wait and gave us a free round of drinks and a free appetizer.  No better way to get to this Yelpers heart then through his stomach.  My temperament was mollified and I was once again happy to be in GD, giddily wondering if I was in the exact same seat as Michael Jordan when he came here after the President's Cup.   On to the food.

    I go the 5 course tasting menu.  To keep this relatively short and sweet I'll put this in a ordered format.  

    Lobster Bisque:  great texture and flavor.  Most bisques I try are too watery and the temperature is too hot or cold, making it taste like some sort of consommé but GD got it right on the money.  

    Oysters with Caviar: NOT oceany despite the oysters and caviar.  simply refreshing with the light cream sauce drizzled over the oyster.

    Horseradish Crusted Salmon: Cooked to perfection.    It really melted in the mouth and the dilled cucumbers gave it a nice little kick.

    Lamb: I must say this was one of the low point of the meal.  The lamb shoulder was marvelous and great by all accounts but the lamb loin cuts were a bit off the mark by being a bit chewy from being slightly  overcooked.  

    Cheese:  ummm not a big connaisseur of cheese.  not even going to try to be pretentious and claim i could detect the slight oaky aroma coming from the gouda or the herby texture of the bleu cheese.  it tasted how fancy cheese should taste.  to each his (or her) own.

    chocolate souffle:  now heres a dish I can get behind.  The only way I can accurately describe this dish is the fact that after the cheese I was BEYOND stuffed and somehow the souffle was finished.  A real testament to its quality and tastiness

    Overall, you won't get a similar experience to Gary Danko.  I'm not use to super friendly service and it was very refreshing to see this.  They also give you so many free extras that makes asians such as myself very happy.

    1 check-in

    stepping into gary danko is like stepping into a time capsule circa 1980s: completely blacked out windows, crystalline tree branches reflected by mirrors and just-so lighting, creating a dramatic main dining room focal point. tendrilous and elegant super flower bouquets mixed with black and gold masculine finishes. a small bar with a wine list the size of the new testament. gleaming cheese trays and dessert tiers, and an uber-professional staff that works the room like a well-oiled machine, complete with regular rotations similar to military mobilization.

    one thing's for sure: you will never find yourself wanting-- the service is PHENOMENAL.

    freebies:
    - a fun duck liver dumpling w/ carmelized onions and panko amuse bouche
    - truly delicious gary danko breakfast bun for the ladies (tasted like a carrot cake with cream cheese filling and top) and a leather pocket notebook for the men
    - gary danko matchbox giveaways (old school, baby!)

    i ordered the black truffle 5-course tasting menu with wine pairings (menu and wine pairings available on the GD website). all exceptional and beautiful. wines were presented and explained impeccably by master sommeliers, and the timing was perfect. one quip is that the black truffle wasn't as "truffley" as it could have been, that is-- the dishes presented were big on flavor and i expected more truffle in order for it to become the star.

    favorites:
    - the SO's red pumpkin soup with chive biscuit
    - crispy farm egg with white polenta and black/white truffles
    - seared scallops with parsnip potato puree and black truffle sauce
    - wine: 2004 barolo, massolino-- paired with beef tenderloin
    - cheese tray was super informative (up to 4 different cheese selections)

    meh:
    - black truffle cremeux dessert. it tasted really waxy to me.

    tip: book at least 6 weeks in advance. it's easier to reschedule/alter an existing reservation than to try and perfectly time your call for a specific date and time.

    4/15/2009

    Actually, I would probably give this two and a half stars, if I could. Two seems a little harsh, considering the service was some of the best I've ever received, but the food was so many kinds of underwhelming I don't even know where to begin.

    This is one of those restaurants that you rank up there with Manresa, French Laundry, Boulud, etc. So you go in knowing you're going to pay the equivalent of a month's rent. But you've saved, it's a special occasion, you are prepared. You are also prepared to be wowed and dazzled like you've never been wowed and dazzled before.

    Wife and I went for my birthday. I was shocked when I called just five days before the day and got a reservation. I don't know if it's the economy or if more and more people are having the same experience I had there. Anyway, when I called, they asked whether it was a special occasion, and I told the reservationist that it was my birthday.

    We walked in and immediately the service was a cut above. We were so impressed with everyone from the valet to the hostess to our waitstaff, who knew the menu so well it boggled the mind. The sommelier was also personable and highly knowledgable, as one would expect. My wife and I each chose the four-course meal with wine pairings and settled in to be blown away.

    My first course was the crab salad with Meyer lemon aioli. I couldn't believe it--the crab was SWIMMING in aioli. Crab is a delicate shellfish, not something that should be drenched in mayo. My wife started with the lobster and rock shrimp risotto, which was unbelieveably salty. Not so salty it was inedible, but salty enough to where salt was the predominant flavor.

    Not to pick nits here, but I'm sorry, at a restaurant of this caliber you want no mistakes, and right out of the gate, with our first two dishes, were two seriously amateur mistakes. Over-dressing and over-salting can happen to the best line cook, but it's pretty irritating when it's happening during your once-in-a-lifetime dining experience at a restaurant you think should know better.

    My second course was the roasted lobster, which was over-cooked and slightly rubbery. Again, nothing up to this point was inedible, but it was just profoundly disappointing. My first two dishes were flawed in some very basic ways.

    Our third courses--the Guinea hen breast for me and the duck breast for my wife--were very well-executed. Her duck breast was probably the highlight of the meal. The duck hash it came with was stellar, perfectly cooked, perfectly seasoned.

    Wife got the cheese plate as her fourth course, which was mind-blowing. Again, our server did not disappoint. She definitely knew her cheeses and helped us select four that she thought we'd enjoy based on what we were telling her we liked. My trio of macaroons was also phenomenal. I'm not much of a dessert person, but these were out of this world.

    I should also state that the pairings the sommelier picked for us were spot-on. He did a fantastic job as well. The staff here is amazing.

    However, the final blow was that they sent out a cheesecake with "Happy Birthday" written on the rim of the plate, with a little candle. We hadn't ordered it, so I'm assuming they knew it was my birthday when I called and made the ressie. It was charming and a nice gesture. The cheesecake itself, though, tasted a bit like a Costco cheesecake. You know how sometimes lemony desserts can veer into that dangerous territory of tasting a little like lemon-scented Pledge? This was that. To make matters worse, when my wife checked her receipt the next day, she discovered that they had charged us not for two four-course meals, but for one four-course and one five-course meal, and we deduced that they must have considered my cheesecake as a fifth course...even though we didn't order it! It ceases to become a nice gesture when they charge you for it behind your back.

    Anyway, I'm not normally this nitpicky, really I'm not. If I'm at someplace like Delfina, I can overlook a line cook who got a little heavy handed with the salt or a shellfish that stayed in the pot a little too long. But when you're talking this level of professionalism and this price range, I'm looking for flawless. Interestingly enough, I've had several people tell me they also had the same underwhelming experience there as well.

    Yes the food was still well above average and some of it was even innovative (though not incredibly so). And yes, the staff here provides impeccable service. But overall, I couldn't help being disappointed as I walked away from Gary Danko. I'm glad I went once, just for the experience, but I don't think I'll be making a second trip. It'd be nice to go back to see if they were just having an off night, but unfortunately their prices preclude that, so I fear this will be my one GD experience, and it was pretty lackluster.

    5/5 stars**.  If it were possible to Gary Danko six stars, I would.  Believe the hype.  Possibly one of the best meals I've had...ever.  Our group of five had several favorites:
    - Appetizers: Lobster Risotto, Lobster Salad and Sweet Corn Soup w Crab.
    -Entrees: Horseradish Crusted Salmon, Roasted Pork Belly, Lemon Pepper Duck Breast
    -Dessert: Chocolate Souffle, French Macaroon Ice Cream Sandwiches, Roaster Pear with Gingerbread and Nutmeg ice cream

    Ambiance: The windows are blacked out, which allows for a very controlled environment.  Lighting is just right and noise levels are low enough to allow for good conversation.  Although staff are constantly attending to guests, the overall mood remains calm.

    Service: The staff goes out of its way to be extremely friendly, gracious, observant and detail oriented.  From the moment you walk in to the final goodbye, the staff delivers rockstar treatment.  Decorative hooks are provided for women to conveniently hang their handbags on the edge of the table.  Water is poured in a way that minimizes potential splashes.  Women are given a "going away present" at the end of dinner.

    Flexibility:  The menu has a plethora of options and you order based on your preference for a three, four or five course dinner.  You're not limited to one dish from each category either so theoretically you could have a dinner of five appetizers or five desserts if you wanted.

    Facilities: Valet parking is available for $11, but we found street parking a couple of blocks away.  There are three unisex restrooms, all of which could almost double as fancy massage treatment rooms.  Just replace the toilet with a massage table.

    Ultimately, it's difficult to find anything negative to say about Restaurant Gary Danko, other than the price.  I would definitely recommend this place for special occasions.
